$e^{j\theta}=cos(\theta)+jsin(\theta)$
$(e^{j\theta})^{*}=cos(\theta)-jsin(\theta)$
$cos(\theta)=\frac{e^{j\theta}+e^{-j\theta}}{2}$
$sin(\theta)=\frac{e^{j\theta}-e^{-j\theta}}{2j}$

Continuous Time Fourier Series
==============================

+ Definition of periodicity: $x(t+\tau)=x(t) \forall t$
+ Write x(t) as a weighted sum of $e^{jk \omega_0 t}, k=\cdots,-1,0,1,\cdots$
+ $a_k=(a_{-k})*$, so for real signals, $a_k=(a_{-k})*$

Finding the Fourier Series Coefficients
---------------------------------------

+ $\int_{T} x(t) e^{jn\omega t} dt=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty} a_k \int e^{jk\omega_0 t}e^{-jn\omega_0 t} dt = Ta_n$
+ So a_n=\frac{1}{T} \int_{T} x(t)e^{-jn\omega_0 t}

Discrete Time Fourier Series
============================

+ Definition of periodicity: $x[n+N]=x[n] \forall n$
+ Is cos(n) periodic? **No!** 
+ $cos(\omega_0 (n+N)) = cos(\omega_0 n)$
+ $\omega_0 N = 2\pi M$ then periodic with period $N$.
+ Examples
	+ $cos(\frac{5\pi}{7}n), N=14$
	+ $sin(\frac{\pi}{5}n), N=10$
	+ $cos(\frac{5\pi}{7}n)+sin(\frac{\pi}{5}n), N=lcm(14,10)=70$
+ x[n]=\sum_{k=<N>} a_k e^{jk\omega_0 n}
+ Properties of $\phi_k [n] = e^{jk\omega_0 n}$
	+ $\phi_k[n+N]=\phi_k [n]$
	+ $\phi_{k+N} [n] = \phi_k [n]$
	+ $\phi_k [n]*\phi_m [n] = \mbox{N if k=0 else 0}$
	+ $\phi_k[n]*\\phi_m[n]=\phi_{k+m}[n]$
+ A useful identity: $1+x+x^2+\cdots+x^M=\frac{1-x^{M+1}}{1-x}$
